<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>name@<tt?>name</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>name</tt?> tag is used to define the name of the software being
packaged.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Name: cdplayer
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-name">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>version</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>version</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>version@<tt?>version</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>version</tt?> tag defines the version of the software being
packaged.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Version: 1.2
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-version">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>release</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>release</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>release@<tt?>release</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>release</tt?> tag can be thought of as the <emphasis>package's</emphasis>
version.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Release: 5
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-release">.

</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2 id="s2-rpm-specref-">
<title>Descriptive Tags</title>
<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%description</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>%description</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>description@<tt?>%description</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%description</tt?> tag is used to define an in-depth description of
the packaged software.  In the descriptive text, a space in the first
column indicates that that line of text should be presented to user as-is,
with no formatting done by RPM.  Blank lines in the descriptive text denote
paragraphs.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%description
 It slices!
 It dices!
 It's a CD player app that can't be beat.

By using the resonant frequency of the CD itself, it is able to simulate
20X oversampling.  This leads to sound quality that cannot be equaled with
more mundane software...
</screen>
</figure>
The <tt?>%description</tt?> tag can be made specific to a particular
subpackage by adding the subpackage name, and optionally, the <tt?>-n</tt?>
option:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%description bar

%description -n bar
</screen>
</figure>
The subpackage name and usage of the <tt?>-n</tt?> option must match those
defined with the <tt?>%package</tt?> directive.

See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-description">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>summary</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>summary</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>summary@<tt?>summary</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>summary</tt?> tag is used to define a one-line description of the
packaged software.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Summary: A CD player app that rocks!
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-summary">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>copyright</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>copyright</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>copyright@<tt?>copyright</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>copyright</tt?> tag is used to define the copyright terms applicable
to the software being packaged.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Copyright: GPL
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-copyright">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>distribution</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>distribution</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>distribution@<tt?>distribution</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>distribution</tt?> tag is used to define a group of packages, of
which this package is a part.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Distribution: Doors '95
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-distribution">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>icon</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>icon</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>icon@<tt?>icon</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>icon</tt?> tag is used to name a file containing an icon
representing the packaged software.  The file may be in either GIF or XPM
format, although XPM is preferred.  In either case, the background of the
icon should be transparent.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Icon: foo.xpm
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-icon">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>vendor</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>vendor</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>vendor@<tt?>vendor</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>vendor</tt?> tag is used to define the name of the entity that is
responsible for packaging the software.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Vendor: White Socks Software, Inc.
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-vendor">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>url</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>url</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>url@<tt?>url</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>url</tt?> tag is used to define a Uniform Resource Locator that can
be used to obtain additional information about the packaged software.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
URL: http://www.gnomovision.com/cdplayer.html
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-url">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>group</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>group</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>group@<tt?>group</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>group</tt?> tag is used to group packages together by the types of
functionality they provide.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Group: Applications/Editors
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-group">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>packager</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>packager</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>packager@<tt?>packager</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>packager</tt?> tag is used to hold the name and contact information
for the person or persons who built the package.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Packager: Fred Foonly &lt;fred@gnomovision.com&gt;
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-packager">.

</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2 id="s2-rpm-specref-">
<title>Dependency Tags</title>
<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>provides</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>provides</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>provides@<tt?>provides</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>provides</tt?> tag is used to specify a "virtual package" that the
packaged software makes available when it is installed.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Provides: module-info
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-provides">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>requires</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>requires</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>requires@<tt?>requires</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>requires</tt?> tag is used to alert RPM to the fact that the package
needs to have certain capabilities available in order to operate properly.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Requires: playmidi
</screen>
</figure>
A version may be specified, following the package specification.  The
following comparison operators may be placed between the package and
version:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
&lt;, &gt;, =, &gt;=, or &lt;=
</screen>
</figure>
<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Requires: playmidi &gt;= 2.3
</screen>
</figure>
If the <tt?>Requires</tt?> tag needs to perform a comparison against a serial
numbered defined with the <tt?>serial</tt?> tag, then the proper format would
be:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Requires: playmidi =S 4
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-requires">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>serial</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>serial</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>serial@<tt?>serial</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>serial</tt?> tag is used to define a serial number for a package.
This is only necessary if RPM is unable to determine the ordering of
a package's version numbers.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Serial: 4
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-serial">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>conflicts</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>conflicts</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>conflicts@<tt?>conflicts</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>conflicts</tt?> tag is used to alert RPM to the fact that the
package is not compatible with other packages.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Conflicts: playmidi
</screen>
</figure>
A version may be specified, following the package specification.  The
following comparison operators may be placed between the package and
version:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
&lt;, &gt;, =, &gt;=, or &lt;=
</screen>
</figure>
<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Conflicts: playmidi &gt;= 2.3
</screen>
</figure>
If the <tt?>conflicts</tt?> tag needs to perform a comparison against a
serial numbered defined with the <tt?>serial</tt?> tag, then the proper
format would be:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Conflicts: playmidi =S 4
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-conflicts">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>autoreqprov</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>autoreqprov</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>autoreqprov@<tt?>autoreqprov</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>autoreqprov</tt?> tag is used to control the automatic dependency
processing performed when the package is being built.  To disable automatic
dependency processing, add the following line:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
AutoReqProv: no
</screen>
</figure>
(The number <tt?>0</tt?> may be used instead of <tt?>no</tt?>)  Although RPM
defaults to performing automatic dependency processing, the effect of the
<tt?>autoreqprov</tt?> tag can be reversed by changing <tt?>no</tt?> to
<tt?>yes</tt?>.  (The number <tt?>1</tt?> may be used instead of <tt?>yes</tt?>)

See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-autoreqprov">.

</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2 id="s2-rpm-specref-">
<title>Architecture- and Operating System-Specific Tags</title>
<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>excludearch</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>excludearch</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>excludearch@<tt?>excludearch</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>excludearch</tt?> tag is used to direct RPM to ensure that the
package does <emphasis>not</emphasis> attempt to build on the excluded architecture(s).

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
ExcludeArch: sparc alpha
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-excludearch">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>exclusivearch</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>exclusivearch</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>exclusivearch@<tt?>exclusivearch</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>exclusivearch</tt?> tag is used to direct RPM to ensure the package
is <emphasis>only</emphasis> built on the specified architecture(s).

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
ExclusiveArch: sparc alpha
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-exclusivearch">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>excludeos</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>excludeos</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>excludeos@<tt?>excludeos</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>excludeos</tt?> tag is used to direct RPM to ensure that the package
does <emphasis>not</emphasis> attempt to build on the excluded operating system(s).

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
ExcludeOS: linux irix
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-excludeos">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>exclusiveos</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>exclusiveos</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>exclusiveos@<tt?>exclusiveos</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>exclusiveos</tt?> tag is used to denote which operating system(s)
should <emphasis>only</emphasis> be be permitted to build the package.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
ExclusiveOS: linux
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-exclusiveos">.

</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2 id="s2-rpm-specref-">
<title>Directory-related Tags</title>
<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>prefix</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>prefix</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>prefix@<tt?>prefix</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>prefix</tt?> tag is used to define part of the path RPM will use
when installing the package's files.  The prefix can be redefined by the
user when the package is installed, thereby changing where the package is
installed.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Prefix: /opt
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-prefix">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>buildroot</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>buildroot</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>buildroot@<tt?>buildroot</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>buildroot</tt?> tag is used to define an alternate build root, where
the software will be installed during the build process.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
BuildRoot: /tmp/cdplayer
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-buildroot">.

</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2 id="s2-rpm-specref-">
<title>Source and Patch Tags</title>
<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>source</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>source</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>source@<tt?>source</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>source</tt?> tag is used to define the filename of the sources to be
packaged.  When there is more than one <tt?>source</tt?> tag in a spec file,
each one must be numbered so they are unique, starting with the number
<tt?>0</tt?>.  When there is only one tag, it does not need to be numbered.

By convention, the source filename is usually preceded by a URL pointing to
the location of the original sources, but RPM does not require this.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Source0: ftp://ftp.gnomovision.com/pub/cdplayer-1.0.tgz
Source1: foo.tgz
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-source">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>nosource</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!tags in!<tt?>nosource</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>nosource@<tt?>nosource</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>nosource</tt?> tag is used to alert RPM to the fact that one or more
source files should be excluded from the source package file.  The tag is
followed by one or more numbers.  The numbers correspond to the numbers
following the <tt?>source</tt?> tags that are to be excluded from packaging.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
NoSource: 0, 3
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-nosource">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>patch</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>patch@<tt?>patch</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>patch</tt?> tag is used to define the name of a patch file to be
applied to the package's sources.  When there is more than one
<tt?>patch</tt?> tag in a spec file, each one must be numbered so they are
unique, starting with the number <tt?>0</tt?>.  When there is only one tag,
it does not need to be numbered.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Patch: cdp-0.33-fsstnd.patch
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-patch">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>nopatch</tt?> Tag</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>nopatch@<tt?>nopatch</tt?> tag</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>nopatch</tt?> tag is used to alert RPM to the fact that one or more
patch files should be excluded from the source package file.  The tag is
followed by one or more numbers.  The numbers correspond to the numbers
following the <tt?>patch</tt?> tags that are to be excluded from packaging.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
NoPatch: 2 3
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-nopatch">.

</sect3>

</sect2>

</sect1>

