<sect1 id="s1-rpm-specref-">
<title>Macros</title>
<sect2 id="s2-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%setup</tt?> Macro</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!macros in!<tt?>%setup</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>setup@<tt?>%setup</tt?> macro</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%setup</tt?> macro is used to unpack the original sources in
preparation for the build.  It is used in the <tt?>%prep</tt?> script:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%prep
%setup
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-setup">.

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>-n <emphasis>&lt;name&gt;</tt?></emphasis> Option</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!macros in!<tt?>%setup</tt?>, options to</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>setup@<tt?>%setup</tt?> macro!options to</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>-n</tt?> option is used to set the name of the software's build
directory.  This is necessary only when the source archive unpacks into a
directory named other than <tt?>&lt;name&gt;-&lt;version&gt;</tt?>.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%setup -n cd-player
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-setup-n">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>-c</tt?> Option</title>
The <tt?>-c</tt?> option is used to direct <tt?>%setup</tt?> to create the
top-level build directory before unpacking the sources.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%setup -c
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-setup-c">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>-D</tt?> Option</title>
The <tt?>-D</tt?> option is used to direct <tt?>%setup</tt?> to not delete the
build directory prior to unpacking the sources.  This option is used when
more than one source archive is to be unpacked into the build directory,
normally with the <tt?>-b</tt?> or <tt?>-a</tt?> options.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%setup -D -T -b 3
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-setup-D">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>-T</tt?> Option</title>
The <tt?>-T</tt?> option is used to direct <tt?>%setup</tt?> to not perform
the default unpacking of the source archive specified by the first
<tt?>source</tt?> tag.  It is used with the <tt?>-a</tt?> or <tt?>-b</tt?>
options.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%setup -D -T -a 1
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-setup-T">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>-b &lt;<emphasis>n</tt?>&gt;</emphasis> Option</title>
The <tt?>-b</tt?> option is used to direct <tt?>%setup</tt?> to unpack the
source archive specified on the <emphasis>n</emphasis>th <tt?>source</tt?> tag line before
changing directory into the build directory.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%setup -D -T -b 2
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-setup-b">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>-a &lt;<emphasis>n</tt?>&gt;</emphasis> Option</title>
The <tt?>-a</tt?> option is used to direct <tt?>%setup</tt?> to unpack the
source archive specified on the <emphasis>n</emphasis>th <tt?>source</tt?> tag line after
changing directory into the build directory.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%setup -D -T -a 5
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-setup-a">.

<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!macros in!<tt?>%setup</tt?>, options to|)</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>setup@<tt?>%setup</tt?> macro!options to|)</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2 id="s2-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%patch</tt?> Macro</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!macros in!<tt?>%patch</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>patch@<tt?>%patch</tt?> macro</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%patch</tt?> macro, as its name implies, is used to apply patches
to the unpacked sources.  With no additional options specified, it will
apply the patch file specified by the <tt?>patch</tt?> (or <tt?>patch0</tt?>)
tag.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%patch
</screen>
</figure>
When there is more than one <tt?>patch</tt?> tag line in a spec file, they
can be specified by appending the number of the <tt?>patch</tt?> tag to the
<tt?>%patch</tt?> macro name itself.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%patch2
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-patch-macro">.

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>-P &lt;<emphasis>n</tt?>&gt;</emphasis> Option</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!macros in!<tt?>%patch</tt?>, options to</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>patch@<tt?>%patch</tt?> macro!options to</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>-P</tt?> option is another method of applying a specific patch.  The
number from the <tt?>patch</tt?> tag follows the <tt?>-P</tt?> option.  The
following <tt?>%patch</tt?> macros both apply the patch specified on the
<tt?>patch2</tt?> tag line:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%patch -P 2

%patch2
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-patch-P">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>-p&lt;<emphasis>#</tt?>&gt;</emphasis> Option</title>
The <tt?>-p</tt?> option is sent directly to the <tt?>patch</tt?> command.  It
is followed by a number which specifies the number of leading slashes (and
the directories in between) to strip from any filenames present in the
patch file.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%patch -p2
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-patch-p">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>-b <emphasis>&lt;name&gt;</tt?></emphasis> Option</title>
When the <tt?>patch</tt?> command is used to apply a patch, unmodified copies
of the files patched are renamed to end with the extension <tt?>.orig</tt?>.
The <tt?>-b</tt?> option is used to change the extension used by
<tt?>patch</tt?>.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%patch -b .fsstnd
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-patch-b">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%patch -E</tt?> Option</title>
The <tt?>-E</tt?> option is sent directly to the <tt?>patch</tt?> command.  It
is used to direct <tt?>patch</tt?> to remove any empty files after the
patches have been applied.

See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-patch-E">.

<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!macros in!<tt?>%patch</tt?>, options to|)</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>patch@<tt?>%patch</tt?> macro!options to|)</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

</sect3>

</sect2>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="s1-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%files</tt?> List</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!<tt?>%files</tt?> list in</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%files</tt?> list indicates which files on the build system are to
be packaged.  The list consists of one file per line.  If a directory is
specified, by default all files and subdirectories will be packaged.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%files
/etc/foo.conf
/sbin/foo
/usr/bin/foocmd
</screen>
</figure>
The <tt?>%files</tt?> list can be made specific to a particular subpackage
by adding the subpackage name, and optionally, the <tt?>-n</tt?> option:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%files bar

%files -n bar
</screen>
</figure>
The subpackage name and usage of the <tt?>-n</tt?> option must match those
defined with the <tt?>%package</tt?> directive.

The <tt?>%files</tt?> list can also use the contents of a file as the list
of files to be packaged.  This is done by using the <tt?>-f</tt?> option,
which is then followed by a filename:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%files -f files.list
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-files">.

<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!<tt?>%files</tt?> list in|)</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="s1-rpm-specref-">
<title>Directives For the <tt?>\%files</tt?> list</title>
<sect2 id="s2-rpm-specref-">
<title>File-related Directives</title>
<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%doc</tt?> Directive</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!directives in!<tt?>%doc</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>doc@<tt?>%doc</tt?> directive</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%doc</tt?> directive flags the filename(s) that follow as being
documentation.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%doc README
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-doc">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%config</tt?> Directive</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!directives in!<tt?>%config</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>config@<tt?>%config</tt?> directive</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%config</tt?> directive is used to flag the specified file as being
a configuration file.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%config /etc/fstab
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-config">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%attr</tt?> Directive</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!directives in!<tt?>%attr</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>attr@<tt?>%attr</tt?> directive</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%attr</tt?> directive is used to permit RPM to directly control a
file's permissions and ownership.  It is normally used when non-root users
build packages.  The <tt?>%attr</tt?> directive has the following format:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%attr(&lt;mode&gt;, &lt;user&gt;, &lt;group&gt;) <emphasis>file</emphasis>
</screen>
</figure>
The user and group identifiers must be non-numeric.  Attributes that do not
need to be set by <tt?>%attr</tt?> may be replaced with a dash:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%attr(755, root, -) foo.bar
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-attr">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%verify</tt?> Directive</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!directives in!<tt?>%verify</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>verify@<tt?>%verify</tt?> directive</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%verify</tt?> directive is used to control which of nine different
file attributes are to be verified by RPM.  The attributes are:

<orderedlist>
<listitem>
<para>
<tt?>owner</tt?> --- The file's owner.

</para>
</listitem>

<listitem>
<para>
<tt?>group</tt?> --- The file's group.

</para>
</listitem>

<listitem>
<para>
<tt?>mode</tt?> --- The file's mode.

</para>
</listitem>

<listitem>
<para>
<tt?>md5</tt?> --- The file's MD5 checksum.

</para>
</listitem>

<listitem>
<para>
<tt?>size</tt?> --- The file's size.

</para>
</listitem>

<listitem>
<para>
<tt?>maj</tt?> --- The file's major number.

</para>
</listitem>

<listitem>
<para>
<tt?>min</tt?> --- The file's minor number.

</para>
</listitem>

<listitem>
<para>
<tt?>symlink</tt?> --- The file's symbolic link string.

</para>
</listitem>

<listitem>
<para>
<tt?>mtime</tt?> --- The file's modification time.

</para>
</listitem>

</orderedlist>
If the keyword <tt?>not</tt?> precedes the list, every attribute
<emphasis>except</emphasis> those listed will be verified.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%verify(mode md5 size maj min symlink mtime) /dev/ttyS0
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-verify">.

</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2 id="s2-rpm-specref-">
<title>Directory-related Directives</title>
<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%docdir</tt?> Directive</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!directives in!<tt?>%docdir</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>docdir@<tt?>%docdir</tt?> directive</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%docdir</tt?> directive is used to add the specified directory to
RPM's internal list of directories containing documentation.  When a
directory is added to this list, every file packaged in this directory (and
any subdirectories) will automatically be marked as documentation.

See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-docdir">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%dir</tt?> Directive</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!directives in!<tt?>%dir</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>dir@<tt?>%dir</tt?> directive</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%dir</tt?> directive is used to direct RPM to package only the
directory itself, regardless of what files may reside in the directory at
the time the package is created.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%dir /usr/blather
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-dir">.

</sect3>

</sect2>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="s1-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%package</tt?> Directive</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>package@<tt?>%package</tt?> directive</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%package</tt?> directive is used to control the creation of
subpackages.  The subpackage name is derived from the first <tt?>name</tt?>
tag in the spec file, followed by the name specified after the
<tt?>%package</tt?> directive.  Therefore, if the first <tt?>name</tt?> tag
is:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
Name: foo
</screen>
</figure>
and a subpackage is defined with the following <tt?>%package</tt?>
directive:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%package bar
</screen>
</figure>
the subpackage name will be <tt?>foo-bar</tt?>.

See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-package">.

<sect2 id="s2-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%package -n</tt?> Option</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!directives in!<tt?>%package</tt?>, options to</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>package@<tt?>%package</tt?> directive!<tt?>-n</tt?> option</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>-n</tt?> option is used to change how RPM derives the subpackage
name.  When the <tt?>-n</tt?> option is used, the name following the
<tt?>%package</tt?> directive becomes the complete subpackage name.
Therefore, if a subpackage is defined with the following <tt?>%package</tt?>
directive:

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%package -n bar
</screen>
</figure>
the subpackage name will be <tt?>bar</tt?>.

See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-package-n">.

<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!directives in!<tt?>%package</tt?>, options to|)</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>package@<tt?>%package</tt?> directive!<tt?>-n</tt?> option|)</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

</sect2>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="s1-rpm-specref-">
<title>Conditionals</title>
The <tt?>%if<emphasis>xxx</tt?></emphasis> conditionals are used to begin a section of the
spec file that is specific to a particular architecture or operating
system.  They are followed by one or more architecture or operating system
specifiers, each separated by commas or whitespace.

Conditionals may be nested within other conditionals, provided that the
inner conditional is completely enclosed by the outer conditional.

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%ifarch</tt?> Conditional</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!conditionals in!<tt?>%ifarch</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>ifarch@<tt?>%ifarch</tt?> conditional</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

If the build system's architecture is specified, the part of the spec file
following the <tt?>%ifarch</tt?>, but before a <tt?>%else</tt?> or
<tt?>%endif</tt?> will be used during the build.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%ifarch i386 sparc
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-ifarch">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%ifnarch</tt?> Conditional</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!conditionals in!<tt?>%ifnarch</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>ifnarch@<tt?>%ifnarch</tt?> conditional</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

If the build system's architecture is specified, the part of the spec file
following the <tt?>%ifarch</tt?> but before a <tt?>%else</tt?> or
<tt?>%endif</tt?> will <emphasis>not</emphasis> be used during the build.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%ifnarch i386 sparc
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-ifnarch">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%ifos</tt?> Conditional</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!conditionals in!<tt?>%ifos</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>ifos@<tt?>%ifos</tt?> conditional</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

If the build system is running one of the specified operating systems, the
part of the spec file following the <tt?>%ifos</tt?> but before a
<tt?>%else</tt?> or <tt?>%endif</tt?> will be used during the build.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%ifos linux
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-ifos">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%ifnos</tt?> Conditional</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!conditionals in!<tt?>%ifnos</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>ifnos@<tt?>%ifnos</tt?> conditional</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

If the build system is running one of the specified operating systems, the
part of the spec file following the <tt?>%ifnos</tt?> but before a
<tt?>%else</tt?> or <tt?>%endif</tt?> will <emphasis>not</emphasis> be used during the
build.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%ifnos linux
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-ifnos">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%else</tt?> Conditional</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!conditionals in!<tt?>%else</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>else@<tt?>%else</tt?> conditional</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

The <tt?>%else</tt?> conditional is placed between a <tt?>%if</tt?>
conditional of some persuasion, and an <tt?>%endif</tt?>.  It is used to
create two blocks of spec file statements, only one of which will be used
in any given case.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%ifarch alpha
make RPM_OPT_FLAGS="$RPM_OPT_FLAGS -I ."
%else
make RPM_OPT_FLAGS="$RPM_OPT_FLAGS"
%endif
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-else">.

</sect3>

<sect3 id="s3-rpm-specref-">
<title>The <tt?>\%endif</tt?> Conditional</title>
<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!conditionals in!<tt?>%endif</tt?></primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

<indexterm>
<primary>endif@<tt?>%endif</tt?> conditional</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

An <tt?>%endif</tt?> is used to end a conditional block of spec file
statements.  The <tt?>%endif</tt?> is always needed after a conditional,
otherwise, the build will fail.

<figure id="sc-rpm-specref-">
<title>*** Enter New Title Here ***</title>
<screen width="60">
%ifarch i386
make INTELFLAG=-DINTEL
%endif
</screen>
</figure>
See also: Section <xref linkend="inside-endif">.

<indexterm>
<primary>spec file!contents of|)</primary>
<secondary></secondary>
<tertiary></tertiary>
<see></see>
</indexterm>

</sect3>

</sect1>

</chapter>

